page.title: 19Dubbs Moss Eaglesfield
page.content: {Dubbs Moss}is a reserve belonging to the{Cumbria Trust for Nature {Conservation.}Its about 1.25 km N.E. of Eaglesfield and is{18 hectares containing of{rough grass, birch wood, {hawthorn and fen land.}So that you don't get lost there is a path, signs and arrows to guide you around. Under foot the ground is{peat.}If you jump up and down you can feel the ground vibrating. When we visited the reserve we did not see a{roe deer}but we heard one. Plantwise we saw bracket fungus, lichen, purple and common spotted orchids, wood sorrel, horse tails, ferns and peat moss. In the wood there are various moths, ferns, flowers and hundreds of midges. There are boxes for tits and an owl box. In the fen land there is a{pond.}Surrounding the reserve there are ditches which is where the{frogs}breed.
